** Stand beside a table or chair, place one hand on it for support. Lean forward slightly, allowing your injured arm to hang down. Gently swing your arm in a small circle, clockwise for one minute, then counterclockwise for another minute. This exercise helps increase shoulder motion and reduce stiffness.

** The two-way kettlebell swing alternates between a chest-height kettlebell swing and an overhead kettlebell swing. Both variations target the hamstrings, glutes, and core, with the overhead swing being more demanding and working the upper back and shoulders. This exercise is great for circuit training or full-body workouts. If you experience lower back or shoulder pain, stick to the chest-height swing.

** Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart. Extend your arms out to the sides at shoulder height. Slowly make small circles with your arms, gradually increasing the size of the circles. This exercise helps improve shoulder mobility and warm up the shoulder muscles.

** Sit or stand with your back straight. Gently pull your shoulder blades together as if you are trying to hold a pencil between them. Hold the squeeze for 5 seconds, then slowly release. This exercise helps improve posture and strengthens the muscles around your shoulder blades.

** Stand with your back against a wall, feet shoulder-width apart. Place your arms against the wall in a 'W' shape, with elbows bent and hands pointing upwards. Slowly slide your arms up the wall into a 'Y' shape, then return to the starting position. This exercise helps improve shoulder mobility and posture.

** Grab a towel and hold it with one hand behind your back, with your palm facing out. Reach over your shoulder with your other hand and grab the top of the towel. Gently pull the towel up with your top hand, stretching your shoulder. Hold for a few seconds, then switch sides. This stretch helps improve shoulder flexibility and reduce tension.

** Stand in a doorway with your arms out to the sides and elbows bent at a 90-degree angle, with your forearms resting on the door frame. Step one foot forward and gently lean into the doorway until you feel a stretch in your chest and shoulders. Hold the stretch for 30 seconds, then step back and relax. This exercise helps improve shoulder flexibility and relieve tension.

** Sit on the floor with your legs extended straight in front of you. Inhale as you lengthen your spine, then exhale and gently reach for your toes, bending at the hips. Hold the stretch for 30 seconds, breathing deeply, and then slowly release. This stretch helps relax your back and hamstrings.

** Stand or sit comfortably with your back straight. Lift your shoulders up towards your ears, roll them back, and then down in a circular motion. Repeat this movement. Shoulder Rolls help relieve tension and improve shoulder flexibility.

** Sit on the floor with your legs extended straight out in front of you. Inhale, and as you exhale, slowly bend forward at the hips, reaching your hands towards your feet. Keep your back straight and go as far as comfortable without straining. This stretch helps to release tension in the lower back and hamstrings.

name: ** Seated Front Deltoid Stretch
description: ** Sit comfortably on a chair with your back straight. Extend your arms in front of you and interlock your fingers. Slowly lift your arms upward, feeling a stretch in your shoulders and the front deltoid muscles. Hold this position for a few seconds, then relax. Repeat the movement for a gentle stretch without overstraining.

name: ** Scapular Retraction
description: ** Stand or sit with a straight back. Keep your arms at your sides, and pull your shoulder blades back and down as if you are trying to pinch a pencil between them. Hold this position for a few seconds and then release. This exercise helps to strengthen the muscles around your shoulder blades, promoting better posture and stability.

name: ** Shoulder Blade Squeeze
description: ** Sit or stand with your back straight. Place your arms by your sides and bend your elbows at a 90-degree angle. Squeeze your shoulder blades together as if you're trying to hold a pencil between them. Hold the squeeze for a few seconds and then release. This exercise helps to strengthen the upper back and improve shoulder posture.

name: ** Wall Angels
description: ** Stand with your back against a wall and your feet a few inches away. Ensure your head, upper back, and buttocks are touching the wall. Raise your arms to shoulder height with elbows bent at 90 degrees, like a goalpost. Slowly slide your arms up and down the wall in a controlled manner, keeping your shoulder blades in contact with the wall throughout. This exercise helps improve shoulder mobility and posture.

name: ** Shoulder External Rotation with Resistance Band
description: ** Secure a resistance band to a stable object at elbow height. Stand sideways with the injured shoulder farthest from the anchor point. Hold the band with the hand of the injured shoulder and bend your elbow to 90 degrees. Keep your elbow close to your body, then slowly rotate your forearm away from your body while keeping your shoulder stable. Return to the starting position in a controlled manner. This exercise helps strengthen the rotator cuff muscles and improve shoulder stability.

name: ** Wall Push-Ups
description: ** Stand facing a wall at arm's length. Place your hands on the wall at shoulder height and shoulder-width apart. Keep your feet firmly planted on the ground, and slowly bend your elbows to bring your chest closer to the wall. Ensure your body forms a straight line from head to heels. Push back to the starting position in a controlled manner. This exercise is great for gently strengthening the shoulder muscles without causing strain.

name: ** Arm Circles
description: ** Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart. Extend your arms straight out to the sides at shoulder height. Slowly make small circles with your arms in a forward motion for about 2 minutes, then reverse the direction for another 2 minutes. This exercise helps improve shoulder mobility and warm-up the muscles gently.

name: ** Seated Leg Extensions
description: ** Sit in a sturdy chair with your back straight and feet flat on the floor. Slowly extend one leg out in front of you, keeping your foot flexed. Hold for a moment, then lower it back down. Repeat for the other leg. This exercise helps to strengthen the quadriceps without putting much strain on the knee.

name: ** Cross-body Shoulder Stretch
description: ** This stretch targets increased flexibility in the shoulders. It's a common inclusion in upper-body dynamic warm-ups to help "limber up" the upper body and can be performed anytime.

name: ** Seated Row with Resistance Band
description: ** This exercise helps strengthen the muscles around the shoulder and upper back, which can aid in improving shoulder stability and reducing pain. Sit on the floor with your legs extended, loop a resistance band around your feet, and hold the ends with your hands. Keep your back straight and pull the band towards you while squeezing your shoulder blades together.

name: ** Shoulder Blade Squeeze
description: ** This exercise helps improve posture and strengthens the muscles between your shoulder blades, which is beneficial for shoulder pain relief. Sit or stand with your arms at your sides. Squeeze your shoulder blades together, hold for a few seconds, and then release. Make sure to keep your shoulders down and relaxed during the exercise.

name: ** Wall Angels
description: ** This exercise helps improve shoulder mobility and posture. Stand with your back against a wall, feet shoulder-width apart. Raise your arms to form a 'W' shape, with elbows bent and hands pointing upwards. Slowly raise your arms to form a 'Y' shape, keeping your arms and back in contact with the wall. Return to the starting position.

name: ** Face Pulls
description: ** Use a resistance band or cable machine. Stand with feet shoulder-width apart. Hold the band or cable with both hands, keeping your arms extended. Pull towards your face, keeping your elbows high and to the sides, squeezing your shoulder blades together. This helps improve shoulder health and posture.

name: ** Wall Angels
description: ** Stand with your back against a wall, feet shoulder-width apart. Keep your arms bent at 90 degrees, and press your elbows and wrists against the wall. Slowly slide your arms up and down the wall, maintaining contact at all points. This exercise helps in improving shoulder mobility and posture.

name: ** Shoulder Dislocation Stretch-Dowel
description: ** This exercise helps to increase shoulder flexibility and range of motion. Use a dowel or a long stick. Hold it with both hands, wider than shoulder-width apart. Slowly raise the dowel over your head and then move it behind your back, keeping your arms straight throughout the movement. Bring it back to the starting position.

name: ** Pendulum Swing
description: ** This exercise helps to gently mobilize your shoulder joint. Lean forward slightly, supporting your non-injured arm on a table or chair. Let your injured arm hang down freely. Begin to gently swing your arm in small circles, using gravity to help move the shoulder joint.

name: ** Seated Leg Press
description: ** Sit comfortably on the leg press machine with your back and head resting against the padded support. Place your feet on the footplate shoulder-width apart. Push the plate away by extending your legs and then slowly return to the starting position. This exercise targets your quadriceps, glutes, and hamstrings.

name: ** Knee Circles
description: ** Stand with your feet slightly apart and place your hands on your knees. Slowly bend your knees and make small circles with them by rotating them in one direction for half the duration, then switch to the opposite direction. This exercise helps improve knee flexibility and mobility.

name: ** Quad Sets
description: ** Sit on the floor with your legs extended in front of you. Place a small rolled towel under your knee. Tighten your thigh muscle, pressing the back of your knee down into the towel. Hold for a count of 5 seconds, then relax. This exercise helps strengthen the quadriceps without putting stress on the knee joint.

name: ** Marching in Place
description: ** Marching in place is a low-impact exercise that helps to increase your heart rate and get your muscles warm without putting much stress on your knees. Simply stand in place and lift your knees towards your chest in an alternating pattern, swinging your arms naturally as you do so.

name: ** One Knee To Chest
description: ** This stretch helps to relieve tension in the glutes and lower back, which can indirectly support knee health by improving overall leg flexibility. Lie on your back with both legs extended. Pull one knee toward your chest while keeping the other leg straight on the floor. Hold for a few seconds and switch legs.

name: ** Knee Circles
description: ** Stand with your feet together and place your hands on your knees. Slowly move your knees in a circular motion, first clockwise and then counterclockwise. This exercise helps improve knee flexibility and warm up the joint.

name: ** Seated Leg Extension
description: ** Sit on a chair with your back straight and feet flat on the floor. Slowly extend your right leg out in front of you, keeping it straight, and hold for a few seconds before lowering it back down. Repeat with the left leg. This exercise helps strengthen the quadriceps without putting too much strain on the knees.

name: ** One Knee to Chest
description: ** This exercise is a gentle stretch designed to relieve tension in the glutes and lower back. Lie on your back with your legs extended. Slowly bring one knee toward your chest, holding it with both hands. Keep the other leg straight and flat on the floor. Hold the stretch for a few seconds and then switch to the other leg.

name: ** Seated Leg Extension
description: ** This exercise helps strengthen the quadriceps without putting too much strain on the knee. Sit on a chair with your feet flat on the floor. Slowly extend one leg out in front of you until it is straight, hold for a moment, then lower it back down to the starting position. Alternate between both legs.

name: ** Partner Facing Feet-Elevated Side Plank With Band Row
description: ** This exercise helps to strengthen your core and improve stability, which can be beneficial for knee support. Place your feet on an elevated surface while in a side plank position. Hold a resistance band with your top hand. While maintaining the plank position, perform a rowing motion by pulling the band towards your ribcage, then return to the starting position. Switch sides after completing the reps.

name: ** Calf Raises
description: ** This exercise helps to strengthen the calf muscles, which can provide additional support to the knees. Stand with your feet hip-width apart, and slowly raise your heels to stand on your toes, then lower back down. To maintain balance, you can hold onto a wall or a chair.

name: ** Seated Leg Raises
description: ** Sit in a chair with your back straight and feet flat on the floor. Slowly extend one leg out in front of you until it's parallel to the ground, hold for a moment, then lower it back down. Alternate between legs. This exercise helps strengthen the quadriceps without putting too much strain on the knee.
